column20: UNESCO - UIS - FY 2008-09cs (UIS) is one of nine specialized institutes of UNESCO, created in 1999 to foster evidence-based policy through the collection and use of high-quality and timely data in education, science and technology, and culture and communication. The UIS has developed the world's most comprehensive education database, and it is the official source of education related targets of the MDGS and Education for All Monitoring Reports. UIS is also the source of education statistics for the World Development Report (World Bank); the Human Development Report (UNDP); and the State of the World's Children (UNICEF). column20: **Project Objectives**: The objectives of this project are to help solve problems of capital shortages for SMEs in Belarus, improve industry competitiveness, and boost the Belorussian economy.  The project aims to provide credit through participating banks to beneficiaries who undertake an eligible sub-project in order to promote the establishment, improvement and expansion of competitive and private sector activity in Belarus and help foster an open market-oriented economy in the country.  **Project Content**: The project involves co-financing with the European Bank for Reconstruction and Development (EBRD), channeling the loan through Belarus' Central Bank and five financial institutions, and implementing 30 sub-projects that will accelerate Belorussian SME development. **Implementation Arrangement**: The National Bank of Belarus is responsible for channeling the loan to commercial banks that will re-lend loans to SMEs.

column18: Dissemination of the National Biodiversity Strategy, Action Plan, First National Report to the CBD & Establishment of the Clearing House Mechanism
column20: description:This project will assist the national Government to meet its obligations under the Convention on Biological Diversity.;other description:Project Objectives and Short Description: The Belarusian biodiversity is being strongly impacted by factors such as extensive agriculture (with high inputs of pesticides and fertilizers which breach the recommended· use), including the transformation of swampy lands which lead to the destruction of critical habitats; pollution; poaching; infrastructure development and lack of effective economic policies which take into account the protection of the environment. . The basic goal of the project is to assist the Government of Belarus formulate a framework for the implementation of the commitments resulting from the ratification of the Convention on Biological Diversity through the preparation of a national biodiversity strategy and action plan to guide the conservation and sustainable use of biological resources of the country. During 1995-1996~ BeJarusian scientists in collaboration with government ministries officials and other authorities whose activities are directly connected with natural resources use and management analysed the state of the biological resources of the country and developed the National Strategy and Action Plan for the Conservation and Sustainable Use of Biodiversity in the Republic of Belarus. The above documents were approved by Resolution No.789 of the Cabinet of Ministers on 26 June 1997. These documents need to be translated in English so that the Republic of Belarus can exchange her experiences with other countries in implementing the Convention and discuss funding possibilities with donor governments and institutions. The Government has also expressed the wish to receive assistance to convene a national workshop to publicize the principles and objectives of the National Biodiversity Strategy and Action Plan to representatives of a broad range of stakeholders in order to determine priority measures, including integration of biodiversity conservation and sustainable use concerns into sectoral plans for major sectors such as agriculture, forestry and wetlands management, for which adequate funding should be sought for implementation. The Government of Belarus is also seeking assistance for the preparation of the first national report to the Convention based on the information contained in the national biodiversity strategy and action plan. The above mentioned workshop planned for representatives of Ininistries, local authorities, scientific and research institutions and nongovernmental environmental organizations (NGOs) to publicize the ~SAP will also provide a forum to agree on the contents of the first national report to the Convention. Finally, under this project, a Clearing House Mechanism (CHM) will be established . through appropriate hardware, software, technical support and training to the national focal point for the CHM in order to accelerate the implementation of the Convention through exchange of information and experiences with other countries. The Ministry of Natural Resources and Environmental Protection has been designated as the focal point for the CHM.;implementation status:Project Completed;

column18: Biomass Energy for Heating and Hot Water Supply
column20: description:The goal of the project is to introduce the environmentally friendly option of biomass energy within the context of the current socio-economic system in Belarus. The intention of the project is not to liberalize the economy of Belarus, and therefore the project has concentrated on the willingness of the government to undertake behaviors that will support the rational use of energy.  It will focus on the following objectives: 1) strengthening institutional capacity to support biomass energy projects; 2) establishing a track record for investments in sustainable biomass energy projects, including both fuel supply and demand; 3) developing straightforward financial “starter” mechanisms in a challenging investment climate that will allow continued financing for biomass energy projects; and 4) overcoming negative perceptions of biomass energy and provide public and private investors with much-needed market information. First, the project will address lack of biomass project experience by facilitating the investment of USD 2.1 million by the Committee on Energy Efficiency and USD 3.4 million by the private and public sectors by 2006 in biomass energy projects. The project will also address financial barriers by establishing a revolving fund with initial capitalization of USD 1.54 million that will be based in part on the GEF contribution and dedicated to the support of biomass energy.;implementation status:The 2nd demonstration site (Mostovdrev CHP) is under adjustment works on back pressure turbine. Biomass-fired boiler was commissioned in September 2007. Trial run and warranty tests for the whole CHP have been shifted to October 2007. The 3rd demonstration site (Vileika CHP) is in operation since September 2007. The site was visited by Prime Minister in September 2007. CHP personnel and boiler manufacturer are involved in adjustment of combustion process to avoid excessive CO emissions. The loan agreement with Vitebskenergo (owner of 5th demonstration site BelGRES CHP) was signed and funds for biomass supply unit equipment procurement transferred. One brochure dedicated utilisation of ash from biomass fired boilers was drafted. One local training session was conducted, with 23 specialists and managers of regional level receiving training in biomass use.;

column7: Belarus (Ministry of Natural Resources & Environmental Protection)
column18: National Capacity Self-Assessment (NCSA) for Global Environment Management
column20: other description:The objective of the NCSA is for Belarus to undertake a capacity assessment so that it can meet its requirements under the global environmental conventions, in particular those pertaining to biodiversity, climate change and land degradation. In addition, it is hoped that the NCSA process will provide an opportunity to facilitate the development of concrete initiatives that will lead to synergistic approaches in addressing global environmental issues at the national and local level. At the same time it will integrate global environmental management objectives to national environmental management and sustainable development frameworks. Furthermore it will facilitate dialogue, information exchange and cooperation amongst Ministries, Scientific Institutions of the Academy of Sciences, NGOs and the private sector and enhance general awareness about the three Conventions countrywide. The main output of the process is expected to be the elaboration of a National Capacity Self Assessment Report and Action Plan.  The project, will run in parallel with ongoing activities such as, the previously mentioned process to prepare a Second National Strategy of Sustainable Development. It has been agreed by project stakeholders that the outputs of the NCSA will contribute to the development of this strategy. As described above, the NCSA will at all stages undergo consultations and information sharing with the Commission on Sustainable Development. Ultimately, the NCSA Report is expected to be endorsed by the Commission on Sustainable Development and incorporated into the Second Sustainable Development Strategy, endorsed by the same commission.;

column7: Belarus (Ministry of Natural Resources & Environmental Protection)
column18: Enabling activities related to the Implementation of the Stockholm Convention on Persistent Organic Pollutants (POPs) in the Republic of Belarus
column20: description:The overall project objective is to develop a National Implementation Plan (NIP) for POPs issues with the assistance of international organisations so that Belarus effectively addresses the reduction and elimination of persistent organic pollutants consistent with the protection of human health and the environment from the effect thereof, and meet its obligations under the Stockholm Convention.   Within this overall objective the following specific objectives have been identified.· - Develop and adopt a comprehensive country driven NIP for reduction and elimination of POPs compliant with the provisions of the Stockholm Convention, including Article 7. - Assess the adequacy of the national regulatory framework and enforcement capacity to meet the country’s obligations under the Convention, identify possibilities for enhancing the current regulatory framework and produce recommendations for institutional strengthening to ensure enforcement. - Strengthen national institutional and technical capacity as required to undertake implementation of the NIP, meet Convention compliance and reporting obligations, facilitate effective information exchange, and participate fully as a Party to the Stockholm Convention in the long term. - Achieve a high level of awareness of the POPs issue and sustained ownership respecting the NIP and international obligations among decision makers. - Achieve a high level of public and stakeholder participation in the development and implementation of the NIP.·Establish a potential for environmental and health POPs monitoring as an integral part of the national environmental and social/hygienic monitoring systems.  - Provide the basis for expedited financing of NIP implementation measures through preparation on the basis of the NIP action plans for specific POPs of a portfolio of investment and capacity related technical assistance proposals potentially eligible for grant financing under the Convention’s permanent financial mechanism and co-financing through financing opportunities offered within the World Bank Country Assistance Strategy (CAS) framework and such opportunities as may be available from other international sources.;implementation status:The project is under implementation and progressing well. A procurement post review mission will be undertaken on October 12-13, 2005 to carry out post review of procurement under this enabling activity.;

column18: Strategic Partnership for Nutrient Reduction in the Danube River and Black Sea - World Bank-GEF Nutrient Reduction Investment Fund: Tranche 3
column20: description:1.The World Bank-GEF Investment Fund (IF) is the investment arm of the GEF Strategic Partnership on the Black Sea/Danube Basin which also funds two regional projects, the Black Sea Ecosystem Recovery Project for the Black Sea littoral countries and the Danube Regional Project in the Danube Basin, both focusing mainly on capacity building activities. The Fund constitutes a proposed envelope of US$70 million, to be approved by the GEF Council in three tranches, to partially grant-finance investment projects in the Black Sea/Danube Basin that aim at nutrient reduction. In May 2001, the GEF Council approved the first tranche of the IF, US$20 million. The second tranche of US$16 million was approved by the Council in May 2002. Eligible areas of intervention for support under the Fund include investments to remediate and mitigate nutrient pollution in municipalities, industry and agriculture, as well as policy and legal reform and capacity building for enhanced monitoring and enforcement. The Investment Fund provides a focused regional framework for country level investments aimed at a common goal of combating eutrophication in the Black Sea and allows for a streamlined approach to project processing by the GEF.   2.This progress report has been prepared to request tranche 3 of the Investment Fund in the amount of US$ 34 million. Following the instructions in paragraph 20 of the IF Project Brief endorsed by the GEF Council in 2001, the report describes the project pipeline and the stage of development of each project proposal, discusses progress to date on program leveraging targets, and addresses cooperation and coordination of the Fund with the regional projects under the Partnership and other key partners.;implementation status:Tranche 3 in the amount of US$34.0 million was approved on May Council 2003.;

The Fund constitutes a proposed envelope of US$70 million, to be approved by the GEF Council in several tranches, to grant-finance investment projects in the Black Sea/Danube Basin that aim at nutrient reduction. column7: United Nations Office of Project Services (UNOPS)
column18: Preparation of A Strategic Action Programme (SAP) for the Dnieper River Basin and Development of SAP Implementation Mechanisms
column20: description:The long-term objectives of the project are to remedy the serious environmental effects of pollution and habitat degradation in the Dnieper River Basin, to ensure sustainable use of its resources, and to protect biodiversity in the basin. This will be catalyzed through the development of both a regional Strategic Action Programme (SAP) as well as individual National Action Programmes (NAP) outlining country and donor commitments to baseline and additional preventive and remedial actions on behalf of the basin. The implementation of incremental (e.g. transboundary issues) components of the SAP would follow in a second phase to this project. The proposed Dnieper River Basin Programme would also work towards enabling the three riparian countries to implement the principles of coordination and cooperation stipulated by the agreement signed in 1992 by the governments of the republics of Russia, Belarus and Ukraine. River basin management capacity both at the level of individual countries and at the regional level would be strengthened, and wider global benefits would accrue to the basin countries as well as those of the Black Sea, an important international water body significantly impacted by human activities within the Dnieper River basin.;implementation status:Activities of the first tranche of this project finished. The tranche 1 of the project was operationally closed in May 2005.;

column18: Strengthening the Network of Training Centers for Protected Area Management through Demonstration of a Tested Approach
column20: description:Protected areas remain the critical foundation of biodiversity conservation, and as such, they will continue to be supported as a major thrust of GEF-3. This project aims to strengthen the sustainability of protected area management through building capacity and disseminating best practices which is consistent with Strategic Pillar I: 'Catalyzing Sustainability of Protected Areas' and Pillar IV: 'Generation and Dissemination of Best Practices for Addressing Current and Emerging Biodiversity Issues'.   The goal of the project 'Strengthening the network of training centers for protected areas management through demonstration of a tested approach' (SNTC) is to improve biodiversity conservation in Northern Eurasia by strengthening the network of training centres for biodiversity conservation in protected areas and adjacent lands. The training centers will serve as catalysts for more effective management of the large protected area (PA) networks in this region.  March 11, 2005: The project has been substantially revised and refocused based on the comments made earlier by the GEFSEC. The revised project goal is to improve biodiversity conservation and rural livelihoods through a better management of protected areas in Northern Eurasia. The project will do so by (1) seeking stronger political support for PA in the region through awareness raising, strengthening of legal PA framework; and 1) improve PA management through the use of modern management tools, including economic and financial tools benefiting both the environment and poor local communities living in or around the PAs.;implementation status:Project undergoing implementation.;

column4: World Bank - International Bank for Reconstruction and Development (IBRD)
column20: The development objective of the Road Upgrading and Modernization Project for Belarus is to reduce transport costs for road users on the upgraded sections of the M5 road, and introduce electronic tolling in Belarus as an efficient cost recovery mechanism. There are three components to the project. The first component of the project is road upgrading. This component will include the upgrading from 2 to 4 lanes of a total of 53 km of the M5 road located between Minsk and Bobrujsk. The second component of the project is modernization of road tolling system. column20: This project paper seeks the approval of the Executive Directors to provide an additional loan to Belarus for the Post-Chernobyl Recovery Project. The additional loan will help finance the costs associated with the scale-up of activities to enhance the impact of this well-performing project at additional sites in the radionuclide-contaminated areas of the Brest, Gomel and Mogilev Oblasts. The investments will be similar to those under the original project, i.e: energy efficiency improvements, including window replacements and energy efficiency lighting in public buildings, rehabilitation of boiler houses and in some cases conversion of boiler houses to mini combined heat and power plants, and also connection of individual homes to natural gas for heating purposes. The major changes will be: (a) increasing the loan disbursement percentage from 80 to 100 percent of all expenditures, (b) revising the monitoring indicators to reflect the scaled-up activities, and (c) extending the closing date for the additional loan by three years from December 31, 2010 to December 31, 2013.

column4: World Bank - International Bank for Reconstruction and Development (IBRD)
column20: This document describes the Development Policy Loan (DPL) for $200 million that supports the Government's program aimed at addressing the social impact of the crisis, while advancing the structural reforms to foster economic recovery. The reforms supported by this operation aim at strengthening social assistance programs to function better as a cushion to protect the poorest and those vulnerable to fall into poverty due to the economic slowdown and future reforms. Moreover, this operation supports a significant structural reform agenda aimed at unlocking new sources of recovery and medium term growth, particularly through further price liberalization, reducing the costs of entry for new businesses, reducing regulatory and administrative costs of operation for the private sector, reducing subsidies, and eliminating inefficient taxes. At the same time, it supports initial steps in setting the legal and institutional basis for an adequate and transparent privatization process.

column20: The objective of the Integrated Solid Waste Management Project for Belarus is to: (i) increase environmental benefits of integrated solid waste management in the City of Grodno through recovery and reuse of recyclable materials; and (ii) strengthen national capacity to manage hazardous wastes associated with Persistent Organic Pollutants (POPs). There are four components to the project. Component one: construction of a mechanical waste separation treatment facility in the City of Grodno. This component is estimated to cost US$ 37 million, financed by a World Bank loan. Funds will finance construction of a 120,000 ton/year modern mechanical separation plant to recover recyclable materials from commercial and household waste. Component two: waste separation management improvements. This component is estimated to cost US$4.0 million, financed from Government budget. The objective is to sequence improvements to separate waste at source so the mechanical solid waste separation facility receives higher-quality dry input materials to process. Component three: POPs stockpile management. This component will cost an estimated US$26.7 million: US$5.5 million financed by a global environment facility (GEF) grant; US$20.6 million financed from Government and enterprise resources; and the balance from international sources such as United Nation Development Program (UNDP), Swedish International Development Authority (SIDA), North Atlantic Treaty Organisation (NATO). Component four: project management and other support activities: managing the solid waste management (SWM) components (I & II) is estimated to cost US$ 2.65 million: the World Bank will finance US$0.4 to support project staff, training, audits, and incremental office operating expenses; Government will finance staffing, monitoring and evaluation, including surveys; other official staffing support from the Ministry of Housing Utilities (MHU) and the Oblast; and office accommodation, operations, and maintenance.

column18: Ensure Universal Access of the Key Affected Populations in Belarus to HIV Prevention, Treatment and Care
column20: As of 2007 the HIV epidemic in Belarus remained concentrated among vulnerable groups, with low prevalence of 0.2 percent among the general population. Although injecting drug use was the initial driver of the epidemic, in recent years unsafe sex has become a prominent risk factor for HIV transmission. The program supported by this grant seeks to continue efforts to control the HIV epidemic in Belarus and to reduce AIDS-related deaths. The program will expand prevention, treatment and care services for most-at-risk populations, injecting drug users, sex workers, men who have sex with men, prisoners, women and youth, and will aim to improve the quality of services through capacity building of the nongovernmental organizations servicing these groups. The program further endeavors to provide prevention services to young people through schools to make treatment with antiretroviral drugs more widely available, to improve laboratory diagnosis and training of health care staff; and to provide TB treatment to HIV patients who need it

column4: Global Fund to Fight Aids, Tuberculosis and Malaria (GFATM)
column18: Strengthening the Support to Vulnerable Groups and Population at Large under the National TB Control Strategy of Belarus and Expanding Access to Quality Diagnosis and Treatment of Drug-Resistant Tuberculosis
column20: The overall Goal of the Grant is To reduce the burden of tuberculosis in Belarus by scaling up the management of drug-resistant tuberculosis.   While further strengthening essential DOTS interventions remains the key requirement for preventing resistance, it has become clear that, in conditions of very high DR-TB burden, timely diagnosis and proper treatment of DR-TB cases are necessary for the overall success in combating the epidemic and achieving TB control targets and disease-related Millennium Development Goals.This proposal targets specifically drug-resistant TB, therefore a sole main Objective was identified: Objective was identified:  To expand the access to quality diagnosis and treatment of drugresistant tuberculosis. Respectively, there is one Service Delivery Area: Management of drugresistant tuberculosis.The proposal aims at scaling up the management  of DR-TB in the country by enrolling a higher number of patients in second-line treatment according to the need. It is foreseen to enrol a total of 2,100 MDR-TB patients over five years from the civilian and penitentiary sectors. The grant is built to support the country’s second application to  the Green Light Committee for expansion of the treatment cohort, which will be submitted by September 2009. The accomplishment of the grant’s Objective will be ensured through strengthening human and infrastructural capacities, upgrading the TB laboratory services and provision of up-to-date treatment of DR-TB cases with appropriate patient support to ensure adherence. The proposal has a country-wide scope and covers the needs of both civilian and penitentiary sectors. It targets all TB patients in the country (about 28,000 over 5 years); a specific group to be reached by the grant are DR-TB patients. The proposed Activities are organized in the following groups:  1. Strengthening national capacities for management of drug-resistant TB 2. Diagnosis of drug-resistant TB cases 3. Treatment of drug-resistant TB cases with patient support 4. Operational research on drug-resistant TB. The proposal aims at expanding access to diagnosis and treatment of DR-TB: all TB patients will have access to drug susceptibility testing and all patients diagnosed with DR-TB will have access to second line treatment. It is expected that on a longer run, the grant will contribute to improving the key TB outcome indicators (case detection rate  and treatment success rate) and decreasing the prevalence of MDR-TB.

column20: The music and art festival BE2GETHER is dedicated to an important tradition of cultural interchange and spread of democracy between EU members, and their closest neighbours. Be2gether is the biggest international festival in the Baltic States, which took place only several metres away from the Lithuanian–Belorussian board. Organizers of the festival will emphasize problems of international political: the cultural isolation of Belarus, the complicated situation of issuance of visas to Belarusians visiting neighbouring countries, and perspectives to develop cooperation between Lithuania and Belarus. To achieve the objectives of the project, a campaign of public relations, press-conferences, marketing games, contests, information published in press, internet sites and etc. will be organized in Belarus.

column20: This project provides for the development of effective security systems and infrastructure at 15 small arms and light weapons (SALW) stockpile storage sites in Belarus. Thus continue reparation of roofs and other necessary construction work, fences reconstruction, reparation of the power line stores, installation of the detection intruder (in the storage and fence), fire-fighting device and software and communications modules. This activities will enable the SALW stockpile management and security within Belarus to be at a level corresponding both to national requirements and to recommendations set out in the UN Integrated Disarmament Demobilization and Reintegration Standards (IDDRS) and the OSCE SALW Best Practice Guide Stockpile Management and Security.

column18: Advancing Human Rights and Democracy in Belarus through Independent Media
column19: ADVANCING HUMAN RIGHTS AND DEMOCRACY IN BELARUS THROUGH INDEPENDENT MEDIA
column20: This project will produce 12 political talk show episodes that are aired to hundreds of thousands of Belarusians. The show, focusing on issues of democracy, civil engagement, human rights and the rule of law, will facilitate unofficial dialogue around challenges facing civil society. The Freedom and Democracy Foundation will sub-contract Belsat, an independent television station that broadcasts into Belarus. The only activity is to produce 12 episodes for Belsat’s talk show Forum (2/month for 6 months) from July to December. Belsat's talk show Forum is considered to be one of the company’s signature productions. The studio talk show will be produced in Vilnius, Lithuania with an in-studio audience. Hosted by a Belarusian journalist, the talk show features various Belarusian experts discussing issues of democracy, human rights, and the rule of law in Belarus. The show’s screenings will occur twice a month, with subsequent and frequent re-runs.

column18: EASTERN EUROPE & CENTRAL ASIA AIDS CONF - MOSCOW, RUSSIA / 2006.05.15-17
column19: EASTERN EUROPE & CENTRAL ASIA AIDS CONF - MOSCOW, RUSSIA / 2006.05.15-17
column20: PROJECT DESCRIPTION: FUNDING REQUESTED OF CIDA'S CONFERENCES AND EVENTS SECRETARIAT TO ENABLE THE PARTICIPATION OF REPRESENTATIVES OF ELIGIBLE COUNTRIES AT THE EASTERN EUROPE AND CENTRAL ASIA AIDS CONFERENCE 2006, TO BE HELD IN MOSCOW FROM MAY 15 TO 17, 2006. THE PURPOSE OF THIS CONFERENCE IS TO MITIGATE THE IMPACT OF HIV/AIDS IN EASTERN EUROPE AND CENTRAL ASIA. AIDS IS A FAST MOVING DISEASE AND THE RESPONSE TO IT NEEDS TO BE AS VERSATILE AS THE VIRUS ITSELF. COMMUNICATION AND THE SHARING OF BEST PRACTICE IS THE KEY TO TURNING AROUND THIS EPIDEMIC. WITH THIS COMPREHENSIVE SKILL BUILDING PROGRAM, THE IMPACT OF THE CONFERENCE WILL BE FELT ACROSS EASTERN EUROPE AND CENTRAL ASIA. THE CONFERENCE WILL ALLOW THE DELEGATES FROM BOTH REGIONS TARGETED TO TAKE COMMON DECISIONS ON THE USE OF INTERVENTIONS WITH PROVEN EFFICACY TO FIGHT HIV/AIDS IN CORRESPONDENT COUNTRIES. THE PROGRAM WILL MIRROR THAT OF THE BIENNIAL INTERNATIONAL AIDS CONFERENCE, WITH THREE PROGRAM COMPONENTS, SCIENCE, COMMUNITY AND LEADERSHIP. THE SCIENTIFIC PROGRAM WILL CONSIST OF CLINICIANS AND RESEARCHERS INVITED TO PROVIDE CRITICAL INSIGHT INTO THE VARIOUS ASPECTS OF ADDRESSING HIV IN THE REGION (RANGING FROM EPIDEMIOLOGICAL SURVEILLANCE TO CLINICAL TREATMENT). THE COMMUNITY PROGRAM WILL HIGHLIGHT THE RESPONSE OF AIDS SERVICE ORGANIZATIONS, NGOS AND PEOPLE LIVING WITH HIV/AIDS AND PROVIDE A FORUM FOR EXCHANGE OF KNOWLEDGE AND EXPERIENCE. THE LEADERSHIP PROGRAM WILL FOCUS ON THE POLITICAL, SOCIAL, BUSINESS AND MEDIA LEADERSHIP THAT IS NECESSARY TO STEM THE EPIDEMIC.EXPECTED IMPACT: AIDS IS A FAST MOVING DISEASE AND THE RESPONSE TO IT NEEDS TO BE AS VERSATILE AS THE VIRUS ITSELF. COMMUNICATION AND THE SHARING OF BEST PRACTICE IS THE KEY TO TURNING AROUND THIS EPIDEMIC. WITH THE CONFERENCE ACTIVITIES INCLUDING A COMPREHENSIVE SKILLS BUILDING PROGRAM AND A COMMUNITY FORUM, THE IMPACT OF THE CONFERENCE SHOULD BE FELT ACROSS EASTERN EUROPE AND CENTRAL ASIA. IT IS HOPED THAT THE CONFERENCE WILL MITIGATE THE IMPACT OF HIV/AIDS IN THIS REGION.EXPECTED OUTPUTS: THE CONFERENCE WILL PROVIDE A UNIQUE AND TIMELY OPPORTUNITY FOR ORGANIZATIONS AND INDIVIDUALS FROM ACROSS EASTERN EUROPE AND CENTRAL ASIA TO SHARE EXPERIENCES AND DEVELOP COMMON APPROACHES TO THE FIGHT AGAINST HIV/AIDS AT A TIME WHEN THE COURSE OF THE EPIDEMIC CAN STILL BE REVERSED. IT WILL LEAD TO COMMON DECISIONS ON THE USE OF INTERVENTIONS WITH PROVEN EFFICACY TO FIGHT HIV/AIDS IN THESE REGIONS.COUNTRIES: RUSSIAN FED. (29.5%), UKRAINE (14.4%), TAJIKISTAN (10.6%), UZBEKISTAN (10.6%), ARMENIA (5.3%), KAZAKHSTAN REP (5.3%), MOLDOVA, REPUB. (3.8%), TURKMENISTAN (3.8%), AZERBAIJAN REP (3%), BELARUS (3%), GEORGIA (3%), KYRGYZSTAN (3%), POLAND (2.3%), BRAZIL (.8%), ESTONIA (.8%), ROMANIA (.8%) SECTORS: 013040 (100%) THEMES: POVERTY REDUCTION, KNOWLEDGE SHARING AND NETWORKING, CAPACITY DEVELOPMENT, PARTICIPATORY DEVELOPMENT, RESEARCH, REGIONAL COOPERATION/INTEGRATION

column20: UNESCO - UIS - FY 2012-13cs (UIS) is one of nine specialized institutes of UNESCO, created in 1999 to foster evidence-based policy through the collection and use of high-quality and timely data in education, science and technology, and culture and communication. The UIS has developed the world's most comprehensive education database, and it is the official source of education related targets of the MDGS and Education for All Monitoring Reports. UIS is also the source of education statistics for the World Development Report (World Bank); the Human Development Report (UNDP); and the State of the World's Children (UNICEF). Assist special populations which may be vulnerable or at-risk on a temporary or chronic basis whose needs are not addressed under emergency humanitarian assistance or other programs. These include groups such as the disabled; orphans, children and at-risk youth; victims of trafficking; victims of gender-based violence; refugees, returnees, ethnic minorities, internally displaced or other socially excluded groups; the elderly; and female heads of household. Depending on circumstances, services may intend to protect groups; mitigate adverse conditions they face, or to remove barriers to help integrate them into society. Components may include measures to increase the capacity of local service and advocacy NGOs and/or professional social workers; to establish public/private service delivery partnerships as well as family and community focused service models; to establish effective referral networks; to develop appropriate service protocols and methods for screening prospective recipients; or to improve public understanding and sensitivity to the needs of the vulnerable. While services provided should not exclude victims of trafficking in persons, programs designed specifically for this group fall under the Peace and Security Objective under the Transnational Crime Area and the Trafficking in Persons and Migrant Smuggling Element.

Student Advising Centers: “EducationUSA” student advising centers will actively promote U.S. higher education by offering information about educational opportunities in the United States and guidance to qualified individuals on how best to access those opportunities. The Embassy’s Public Affairs Section will provide grants to NGOs or institutions of higher learning to serve as official “EducationUSA” student advising centers.

Alumni Programs: Alumni outreach funds will be used by the Embassy’s Public Affairs Section to encourage networking among U.S. program alumni and their colleagues. Through the administration of small grants to organizations whose members include alumni of U.S. programs, the program will allow the Embassy to provide support to organizations or individuals for civil society development such as community development projects, association building and understanding, and youth programs.
Field Support: Funds will be used to provide salaries and support for staff that works on implementation of AEECA-funded public diplomacy programming at the Embassy.

U.S. Embassy Small Grants Program: The U.S. Embassy’s Public Affairs Section will give small grants to local NGOs to support civil society development in Belarus. All proposals are given a technical review in Washington, D.C., prior to a grant being issued by the Embassy.

Speakers Program: The Speakers Program will strengthen public affairs outreach through the use of recognized experts in a variety of policy-relevant fields for in-country training, lectures, workshops, seminars, and consultations. These experts will pass along their practical skills, thereby creating a “multiplier” effect within the host country. The Speakers Programs will provide a wide range of perspectives, promote recognition of fundamental liberties and individual freedoms in the region, and increase civic participation.

column20: Irish Aid acknowledges the role that Irish civil society organisations can play in building public support for Ireland’s aid programme, informing the Irish public through development education programmes, as well as raising awareness of the issues around development assistance. Irish Aid is committed to continuing to support civil society organisations as partners in the attainment of the Millennium Declaration and associated goals for poverty reduction, and in the protection and promotion of human rights.There are seven key objectives that the Civil Society Fund seeks to promote, which coincide with the role of civil society in development cooperation and human rights promotion, and reflect the commitments of the Millennium Development Goals. The Civil Society Fund will support interventions that contribute to: The strengthening of the voice of communities and civil society organisations to influence policy and its implementation, at local national and international levels 2. The prevention of hunger, and the improvement of livelihood security 3. Improved access to essential services, such as education, health care and programmes of HIV prevention, care and support 4. Improved access and control of resources for marginalised communities 5. The promotion and realisation of human rights 6. The promotion of women’s empowerment and gender equality, including initiatives to tackle gender based violence 7. The promotion of environmental sustainability and in particular, initiatives that combat climate change.

column20: Acogida en familias de 37 niñas y niños y 2 monitoras, procedentes de la región bielorrusa de Klimobichi. Se trata de menores que se ven expuestos a las radiaciones producidas por la central nuclear de Chernobil, que continúa teniendo efectos nocivos sobre la salud de la población de la zona

Saneamiento por acogimiento temporal de 40/45 días en familias de niños/as de Bielorrusia víctimas por las radiaciones, sacándolas de las zonas contaminadas para mejorar su salud, aumentando sus defensas con alimentos no contaminados. Realizarlo en un entorno social-familiar que favorezca el trauma de separación de su familia.
Ayuda humanitaria a Klimovichi.
Acogida de niños y niñas de Chernobil, de las zonas rurales de Gomel y Mogilev (Bielorrusia)
PROGRAMA DE ACOGIDA DE MENORES BIELORRUSOS, AÑO 2010
APOYO EN LA CREACIÓN Y MANTENIMIENTO DE INFRAESTRUCTURAS NECESARIAS QUE PERMITAN CHEQUEOS MÉDICOS A POBLACIÓN INFANTIL QUE SUPERA NIVELES CRÍTICOS DE RADIACIÓN EN ALDEAS RURALES DE BIELORRUSIA
Acoger a niños/as bielorrusos para mejorar su salud Aportar una dieta mediterránea Favorecer su salud con el clima de nuestro pais Facilitar la posiblidad de ir a la playa
Este programa ha facilitado la estancia sanitaria en Córdoba de una delegación de 50 niños/as bielorrusos/as víctimas de la catástrofe nuclear de Chernobyl, destinada a la mejora de su salud.

Election Observation is a vital component of Switzerland's activities to promote democracy, human rights and the rule of law worldwide. Each Election Observation Mission is considered a single project in the Human Security Division (HSD). The focus ofthis credit proposal is the upcoming Election Observation Mission to Belarus which is organized by the Organization for Security and Cooperation In Europe (OSCE)/Office for Democratie Institutions and Human Rights (ODIHR). The Swiss Expert Pool (SEP) will participate In this mission with the secondment of approximately 6 - 8 Swiss election observers. Swiss participation In an International élection observation mission promotes visibility and solldarlty In international cooperation.

column18: Financing a Political Adviser for Eastern Europe with focus on Belarus
column19: FINANCING A POLITICAL ADVISER FOR EASTERN EUROPE WITH FOCUS ON BELARUS
column20: Dans le cadre de la présidence suisse du Conseil de l'Europe (CdE) mais également dans le cadre plus général du rapprochement de cette instance avec le Belarus, il a été décidé de renforcer le Secrétariat général avec un expert qui se concentrera sur les développements dans ce pays. Cet expert, basé à Strasbourg mais se déplaçant régulièrement à Minsk, contribuera à la mise en place des projets du CdE au Belarus et veillera à maintenir un lien avec les autorités de ce pays. Les droits humains, et en particulier la mise en place d'un moratoire sur la peine de mort, seront le thème central du suivi dont aura la charge l'expert suisse.

Dans le cadre de la campagne 'Human Rights Activists against the Death Penalty' et au travers de la réalisation de matériel visuel (cahiers d'information, prospectus, stylos, calendriers, posters), de la réalisation d'un film documentaire sur le recours à la peine de mort au Belarus et de la rédaction de textes sur ce sujet sur internet, le projet de l'ONG Viasna vise à mieux sensibiliser la population du Belarus sur la problématique de la peine de mort afin d'encourager un débat public sur la question et potentiellement, avancer vers un moratoire.

column20: Since the presidential elections in December 2010, repression on civil society actors (journalists, human rights defenders, lawyers, activists, students, opposition leaders, etc.) has become an unprecedented phenomenon. The goal of the project, undertaken by The Belarusian Human Rights House in exile and coordinated by the Human Rights House Foundation, is to use United Nations (UN) mechanisms to maintain pressure on Belarus authorities in order to meet with international standards in the field of human rights and to comply with the commitments they have made to the international community. The activities of the project will focus on UN advocacy.

column4: Global Fund to Fight Aids, Tuberculosis and Malaria (GFATM)
column18: Ensure Universal Access of the Key Affected Populations in Belarus to HIV Prevention, Treatment and Care
column19: ENSURE UNIVERSAL ACCESS OF THE KEY AFFECTED POPULATIONS IN BELARUS TO HIV PREVENTION, TREATMENT AND CARE
column20: As of 2007 the HIV epidemic in Belarus remained concentrated among vulnerable groups, with low prevalence of 0.2 percent among the general population. Although injecting drug use was the initial driver of the epidemic, in recent years unsafe sex has become a prominent risk factor for HIV transmission. The program supported by this grant seeks to continue efforts to control the HIV epidemic in Belarus and to reduce AIDS-related deaths. The program will expand prevention, treatment and care services for most-at-risk populations, injecting drug users, sex workers, men who have sex with men, prisoners, women and youth, and will aim to improve the quality of services through capacity building of the nongovernmental organizations servicing these groups. The program further endeavors to provide prevention services to young people through schools to make treatment with antiretroviral drugs more widely available, to improve laboratory diagnosis and training of health care staff; and to provide TB treatment to HIV patients who need it.

column4: Global Fund to Fight Aids, Tuberculosis and Malaria (GFATM)
column18: Strengthening the Support to Vulnerable Groups and Population at Large under the National TB Control Strategy of Belarus and Expanding Access to Quality Diagnosis and Treatment of Drug-Resistant Tuberculosis
column19: STRENGTHENING THE SUPPORT TO VULNERABLE GROUPS AND POPULATION AT LARGE UNDER THE NATIONAL TB CONTROL STRATEGY OF BELARUS
column20: In Belarus, the Tuberculosis (TB) burden remains high despite existing national efforts to combat the disease. There has been a progressive increase both in the number of multidrug-resistant TB (MDR-TB) cases and in the incidence of HIV-associated TB in the recent years. The current grant agreement consolidates the goals and activities of the TB program funded under Round 6 and 9 TB proposals based on the Single Stream of Funding (SSF) scheme. The goal of the program is to reduce the burden of TB in Belarus, including scaling up the management of MDR-TB by enrolling higher number of patients in treatment with second-line drugs. The program will achieve full integration of the DOTS strategy in the practical work of the national healthcare system, and support the National TB Program (NTP) in Belarus from 2011 to 2014 by expanding the coverage and scope of the state-supported TB control activities. The program also plans to provide trainings to medical staff and laboratory personnel from national TB control institutions and the general medical network and envisages to introduce an electronic TB recording and reporting system for collecting and monitoring TB clinical and epidemiological data.

column18: Impact of tobacco taxes and price increases in Ukraine, Russia, and Belarus
column19: IMPACT OF TOBACCO TAXES AND PRICE INCREASES IN UKRAINE, RUSSIA, AND BELARUS
column20: Ukraine, Russia, and Belarus have similar population features, health problems and smoking patterns. Developmental priorities of all these countries to be addressed in this project are related to high mortality rates, primarily due to non-communicable diseases (NCDs). While high smoking rates are known to be the most prominent risk factor for NCDs, most of the tobacco control measures, if any, were implemented only quite recently in all three countries. The experiences in tobacco tax policies were, however, quite different. In order to inform tobacco taxation policies (one of the most effective tobacco control measures available to governments), the overall research question of the study is related to how different tobacco taxation scenarios implemented in three countries will impact cigarette consumption, smoking prevalence, tobacco excise tax revenues, and tobacco smuggling, all of which directly or indirectly influence the population health. The aim will be to inform policy-makers in the three countries how their tobacco taxation policy can better serve public health goals and diminish the burden of tobacco-related diseases and deaths for the current and future generations. The specific objectives of the project are to:-Estimate impact of recent tobacco taxes and prices increases in Ukraine, Russia and Belarus on smoking rates, revenues and household expenditures.-Estimate volumes of smuggling both ''into-the-country'' and ''out-of-country'' and their impact on revenue.-Compare different scenarios for separate tobacco tax increases for each country and for coordinated tax increases.-Develop arguments for tobacco tax increases both for decision makers and the media.-Encourage governments to implement coordinated, large tax increases.
column28: Tax assessment procedures|Drug and substance abuse control and counseling

column20: Project Description: Richmond, Canada / 2007.11.06-08 Funds requested of CIDA's Conferences and Events Secretariat to enable the participation of representatives of eligible countries at the conference. The conference program is being developed around the overarching theme of building disaster resilient communities. Recent years have seen no shortage of reminders that improved management of natural hazards and the reduction of disaster risks must be given the highest priority. The need for a global disaster reduction strategy has been underscored by a string of disasters, most notably the 2004 Indian Ocean tsunami which claimed over 250,000 lives, but also the earthquakes in Pakistan and Indonesia; persistent droughts in Africa; heat waves and fires in Europe; hurricanes in Central America and the United States; and landslides triggered by typhoons in South East Asia. ObjectivesThe primary objectives of the CRHNet are to: · Initiate the development of a Canadian inter-disciplinary and cross-sectoral network of researchers, academics and practitioners to enhance understanding of emergency management in all dimensions and help build Canadian capacity to deal effectively with threats and consequences from all hazards. · Create a Canadian annual forum for dialogue focusing on disaster risk reduction and facilitate policy formulation and adoption of best practices in Canada. · Provide a Canadian venue to learn from the experiences of other countries by inviting internationally reputed scholars, practitioners, and participants to the Symposium and to share Canadian experience and efforts in disaster reduction. Websitehttp://www.jibc.ca/crhnet/Expected Impact: · Decreased post-disaster losses and increased community resilience through implementation of community-based, best practices · Increased collaboration and development of strong national and international policies and strategies based on community capacity building and sustainable developmentExpected Outcomes: · Local and International presentations and dissemination of conference proceedings and knowledge · Change in practice based on research and lessons learned · Supportive and collaborative networks of researchers and practitioners · Improved CRHNet 2007 due to evaluation and carefully documented conference organizational materials · Introduction of new programs based on increased knowledge and awareness of global Network (via CRHNet site)Expected Outputs: · Conference Abstracts · Conference Presentations and Handouts (provided to delegates) · Delegate Contact Information · Conference Evaluation · CIDA Report · Web-based CIDA delegate Support Network (via CRHNet site)Countries: India (27.27%), Nepal (18.18%), Thailand (9.1%), Belarus (9.09%), Brazil (9.09%), Lebanon (9.09%), Sri Lanka (9.09%), Russian Fed. (9.09%) Sectors: 074010 (100%)

column18: National Endowment for Democracy Grant to Music Party Promotional Company (Belarus)
column19: NATIONAL ENDOWMENT FOR DEMOCRACY GRANT TO MUSIC PARTY PROMOTIONAL COMPANY (BELARUS)
column20: To help organize the third 'Be2gether' international music festival (www.b2g.lt/2008/en) that is held on the border of Lithuania and Belarus. NED funding will be used to train Belarusian volunteers who will help organize the June festival, as well as to publicize the event in Belarus and Kaliningrad. The event will include repressed Belarusian bands and promote independent culture, artistic freedom, and youth activism.

column18: National Endowment for Democracy Grant to East European Democratic Center
column19: NATIONAL ENDOWMENT FOR DEMOCRACY GRANT TO EAST EUROPEAN DEMOCRATIC CENTER
column20: To continue assisting the regional independent media in Belarus. The Poland-based EEDC will award 15 to 20 small grants to unregistered bulletins that have developed into newspapers and to regional websites that are working in tandem with local bulletins. In addition, it will conduct two training workshops, one in Poland and one in Ukraine, on web journalism and web construction for 30 journalists and webmasters. A total of 35-40 regional media outlets will be assisted.
column33: Media and free flow of information

column18: National Endowment for Democracy Grant to National Democratic Institute
column19: NATIONAL ENDOWMENT FOR DEMOCRACY GRANT TO NATIONAL DEMOCRATIC INSTITUTE
column20: To help reinvigorate civil society development. NDI will bring together civic leaders from Armenia, Azerbaijan, Belarus, Georgia, Moldova and Ukraine to take stock of trends in civil society-government relations and identify ways in which the international community can provide more effective support and solidarity. NDI will conduct study missions to Poland in cooperation with the European Institute for Democracy (EID) to enable political and civic activists from the Eurasia region to learn from Poland's successful democratic transition.

column18: National Endowment for Democracy Grant to Community Change Center (CCC)
column19: NATIONAL ENDOWMENT FOR DEMOCRACY GRANT TO COMMUNITY CHANGE CENTER (CCC)
column20: To enhance the self-government skills of activists from condominium communities in Belarus' Vitebsk, Minsk, Hrodno, Gomel, Brest and Mogilev regions. The Vilnius-based CCC will organize a three-day study and training visit to Lithuania for 25 community leaders and journalists from Belarus as well as produce and distribute 1,000 copies of a self-government magazine for condominium communities.

column18: National Endowment for Democracy Grant to Transitions Online
column19: NATIONAL ENDOWMENT FOR DEMOCRACY GRANT TO TRANSITIONS ONLINE
column20: To promote independent media and youth activism in Belarus by improving the quantity, quality and impact of pro-democratic bloggers and 'new media' activists. The Czech Republic-based TOL will bring five promising young Belarusian new media practitioners to Prague for a training program, expand its on-the-ground consultations to promising new media start ups in Belarus, develop and release a package of web tools in Belarusian and Russian and bring three participants to an Internet Social Innovations Camp in Slovakia.
column33: Media and free flow of information

column18: National Endowment for Democracy Grant to Kultur Aktiv
column19: NATIONAL ENDOWMENT FOR DEMOCRACY GRANT TO KULTUR AKTIV
column20: To improve the skills of Belarusian youth activists and the effectiveness of their work through a series of trainings, civic projects and networking opportunities. The BelaPlus project will be launched with seminars on project management skills. The Germany-based NGO will select 20 of the best participants for training in Berlin and Kyiv and to take part in an international project marking the 20th anniversary of the fall of the Berlin Wall. At a final two-day conference in Vilnius, 50 young Belarusians will exchange lessons learned from their projects.

column18: National Endowment for Democracy Grant to Lion Society
column19: NATIONAL ENDOWMENT FOR DEMOCRACY GRANT TO LION SOCIETY
column20: To carry out a crossborder training and strategic planning program for Belarusian NGOs. Representatives of approximately 50 Belarusian civil society organizations, including NGOs and independent media, will take part in a series of capacity-building workshops. The four-day training program will take place in Lviv, Ukraine.

column18: National Endowment for Democracy Grant to Association for International Affairs (AMO)
column19: NATIONAL ENDOWMENT FOR DEMOCRACY GRANT TO ASSOCIATION FOR INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS (AMO)
column20: To conduct a series of study and training visits for Belarusian political and civic activists in the Czech Republic. The Prague-based AMO will design a one-month program in democracy-building knowledge and skills for six young activists. The three most promising participants will spend an additional month acquiring more advanced training and experience through an internship with a related Czech NGO or political institution. Finally, one to three projects designed by the activists will be funded and the projects implemented by the participants' organizations.

column18: National Endowment for Democracy Grant to Young Artists' Association - Towards Theater
column19: NATIONAL ENDOWMENT FOR DEMOCRACY GRANT TO YOUNG ARTISTS' ASSOCIATION - TOWARDS THEATER
column20: To support and promote Belarus' independent cultural activists and their cultural heritage. The Poland-based Association will seek out, preserve, restore and catalogue important audio and visual materials threatened with destruction in Belarus, make them available on-line, and expand its electronic archive, which is accessible in four languages (www.baavi.net).

column18: National Endowment for Democracy Grant to Young Artists' Association - Towards Theater
column19: NATIONAL ENDOWMENT FOR DEMOCRACY GRANT TO YOUNG ARTISTS' ASSOCIATION - TOWARDS THEATER
column20: To support and promote Belarus' independent cultural activists and their cultural heritage. The Poland-based Association will seek out, restore and catalogue important independent cultural materials banned by the regime in Belarus, make them available online, and expand its electronic archive, which is accessible in four languages (www.baavi.net).

column18: National Endowment for Democracy Grant to Office for a Democratic Belarus
column19: NATIONAL ENDOWMENT FOR DEMOCRACY GRANT TO OFFICE FOR A DEMOCRATIC BELARUS
column20: To monitor, assess and inform European institutions on the progress of reform in Belarus. The Brussels-based Office will compile reports based on information from the monitoring programs of leading Belarusian NGOs in the fields of human rights, independent media, freedom of association and economic reform. The monthly reports will be disseminated in Brussels and European capitals. Roundtables on the reform process will also be organized during the EU-Belarus 'Dialogue Process.'
column33: Public sector policy and adm. management

column18: National Endowment for Democracy Grant to International Association Civic Belarus
column19: NATIONAL ENDOWMENT FOR DEMOCRACY GRANT TO INTERNATIONAL ASSOCIATION CIVIC BELARUS
column20: To increase the capacity of the third sector in Belarus. The Prague-based Association will organize a series of study visits to the Czech Republic for Belarusian NGO activists, visits of Czech third sector experts to Belarusian NGOs, a seminar for Belarusian small business activists in Lithuania, Czech-Belarusian information exchanges, NGO registration assistance, and expert consultations for Belarus' third sector.

column18: National Endowment for Democracy Grant to Education for Democracy Foundation
column19: NATIONAL ENDOWMENT FOR DEMOCRACY GRANT TO EDUCATION FOR DEMOCRACY FOUNDATION
column20: To expand its civic education and NGO training program in Eurasia. The Poland-based FED will conduct at least 50 workshops in Ukraine, Belarus, Moldova, Central Asia, the Caucasus and Mongolia and expand its activities in Georgia, Tajikistan, Moldova, Azerbaijan and Mongolia. The workshops will provide civic education, leadership, NGO development and train-the-trainer skills. Two competitions for school newspapers and civic education lesson plans will be organized. The FED will maintain its website and produce four training brochures.

column18: Multirateral workshop  Reform of the Prison System
column19: MULTIRATERAL WORKSHOP REFORM OF THE PRISON SYSTEM
column20: Platform of the Eastern Partnership for democracy, good governance and stability is among the priorities of the foreign policy of the Slovak Republic. Based on current negotiations two key areas were identified in which Slovakia could pass its transition experience to Eastern Partnership countries (AM, AZ, BY, GE, MD, UA) and these are the areas of reform of the prison system and fight against corruption. In this context, a four-day introductory seminar Reform of the Prison System was held in Bratislava from 5 - 8 November 2013 within the multilateral program prison reform. Seminar was aimed both to conduct lectures and for the exchange of transformation and integration experience. Also selected Slovak detention facilities were visited. At the same time representatives of the six Eastern Partnership countries shared information about how their own prison systems function as well as they tried to identify areas where mutual consultations and cooperation can be established. Therefore EP countries sent representatives of governemntal and non-governmental sector. Belarus and Ukraine did not send their state representatives to this seminar.

column20: Osnovni namen projekta je omogo?iti ukrajinskim in beloruskim otrokom, ki trpijo za posledicami ?ernobilske nesre?e iz leta 1986 rehabilitacijo in na ta na?in prispevati k izboljšanju njihovega zdravja. Ob parni eksploziji v reaktorju št. 4, je bila notranjost reaktorja izpostavljena, kar je v ozra?je spustilo velike koli?ine radioaktivnega materiala. Radioaktivni oblak je najbolj ogrozil Rusijo, Belorusijo in Ukrajino. Posledice so vidne še danes in številni otroci se soo?ajo s težavami, ki so posledica bolezni dihal, kožnih obolenj ter poškodb gibal. Rde?i križ Slovenije projekt izvaja v sodelovanju z Ukrajinskim rde?im križem in Izvršnim odborom Ministrstva za izobraževanje regije Mogilev v Belorusiji. Otroci, ki so bili v program rehabilitacije v Mladinskem letoviš?u in zdraviliš?u Rde?ega križa Slovenije Debeli rti? vklju?eni v 2013 so bili vklju?eni v program respiratorne fizioterapije, katere namen je ve?ja predihanost plju? (zgornjih, srednjih in spodnjih predelov) in sprostitev, program hidroterapije, katere namen je revitalizirati, vzdrževati in povrniti zdravje organizmu in vaj za vzdržljivost kot na primer jutranji tek, pohod v Resslov gaj, nordijska hoja, trim steza s 17 postajami, vodna aerobika. Vaje za vzdržljivost pripomorejo k ve?ji kostni gostoti, krepitvi mišic, boljši gibljivosti ter pospešujejo sr?ni utrip. Dodatno k rehabilitaciji so otroci preostanek ?asa izkoristili za spoznavanje kulturne dediš?ine Slovenskega primorja, vklju?en pa je bil tudi izlet z barko do Kopra. Med obiskom Se?oveljskih solin so prisluhnili pticam in si ogledali postopek tradicionalne pridelave cenjene piranske soli. Obiskali so Muzej solinarstva, obnovljeno solinarsko hišo, v kateri je ujet izsek iz življenja solinarjev. Otroci so bili vklju?eni v ustvarjalne delavnice, v katerih so na temo morje in obala pokazali svojo ustvarjalno žilico. V Mladinskem zdraviliš?u in letoviš?u Rde?ega križa Slovenije Debeli rti? so otroke v 19. avgusta 2013, obiskali državni sekretar na Ministrstvu za zunanje zadeve dr. Božo Cerar, veleposlanik Ukrajine Mikola Kiril?enko in svetovalka na Veleposlaništvu Belorusije Elena Shpakova.

column20: The international scientific and practical conference 'The Republic of Belarus - The European Union: the Challenges and Prospects of Partnership' is organized on purpose to elaborate the efficient mechanisms of interaction and cooperation between governmental and non-governmental organizations of the European Union, The Republic of Belarus and other eastern neighbors of the EU. column18: Widening the European Dialogue in Moldova
column19: WIDENING THE EUROPEAN DIALOGUE IN MOLDOVA
column20: According to the latest public opinion polls, the public support for integration into the European Union has been critically decreasing in Moldova in recent years. Today, only 54,7% of the MoldovaÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s population would support the EU integration, one of the worst results since 2007, when the support was at 71%. On the other hand, the number of opponents of the EU integration has almost doubled in Moldova, raising from 18% to 30%, while the support for the integration into the Customs Union of Russia, Belarus, and Kazakhstan is now at 55,8%. Given the current situation, the overall objective of this project is to contribute in a realistic way to increasing the pro-European and pro-EU integration support among the Moldovan population via: a.) increasing the awareness of the local and international expert and political community about the real priorities and attitudes of the general public in Moldova; b.) widening the European dialogue and increasing the awareness among the general public in Moldova about the benefits the EU brings to the country; c.) widening the European style of communication with the general public in Moldova.

column20: Programa de acogida temporal de menores bielorrusos afectados por la catástrofe de Chernobyl. Convenio de Colaboración con ANIDA :: Este programa ha facilitado la estancia sanitaria en Córdoba, de dos grupos: el primero, formado por 34 menores y 2 monitoras llegó el 25 de junio y el segundo, formado por 8 menores y 1 monitora viajó el 1 de Agosto. En total, se han atendido este año 42 menores bielorrusos/as (cifra mayor respecto a otros años) víctimas de la catástrofe nuclear de Chernobyl, destinada a la mejora de su salud. Durante esta estancia los/as menores han pasado un reconocimiento médico especializado para aquellos que padecen alguna patología, así como una asistencia odontológica a todos lo/as menores en los centros de salud correspondiente a las familias de acogida. También han disfrutado de actividades recreativas y culturas, destacando el acto municipal de acogida, celebrado el 10 de julio en La Ciudad de los Niños: Por segundo año consecutivo, se dan cita en una jornada de convivencia junto a menores cordobeses y saharauis, y en la que el Alcalde da la bienvenida a los menores que participan en programas de estancia temporal en nuestra ciudad. Además,este año se ha celebrado en Córdoba el I Encuentro Internacional de la Plataforma europea por Chernobyl, con participación de 23 colectivos de Alemania, Irlanda, Reino Unido y España. Y conmemorado el 27 aniversario de la Catástrofe de Chernobyl, celebrándose actos en Córdoba, el 18 y 25 de Abril.

It comprises twenty countries which vary in economic strength, political stability and wealth of natural resources. Since its inception, the Programme has focused on the needs of vulnerable groups and contributed to stability and democratic transition in the region.The goal of the programme is poverty reduction and support for democratic transition in the Balkans, CIS and Central Asia. Projects funded are implemented by Irish and international NGOs. Projects funded to date include a programme to introduce palliative care into the government healthcare system in Albania, a multi-faceted project aimed at supporting the economic and social stabilization of the Roma community in Kosovo, and a programme in Central Asia focusing on improving the capacity of journalists and human rights defenders to investigate and report on human rights abuses

column19: CORE FUNDING 2008/09 TO THE UN-NGLS - UN - NGLS - FY 2008-09
column20: UN - NGLS - FY 2008-09ERNMENTAL LIAISON SERVICE (NGLS) 2008-2009 Core Funding Proposed contribution: $50,000 CDN For over 20 years, NGLS has been present and active at numerous UN conferences and, in the 1980s, expanded its liaison role with the NGO communities through publishing, knowledge sharing and database management. UN-NGLS has a good reputation in the NGO community and acts primarily as a public information point to engage civil society in the UN System. They provide the global NGO community with public, substantive and strategic information through a variety of publications and electronically via their website. Canada supports the view that enhanced participation by civil society in the United Nations will strengthen the institution and make it more relevant, responsive and accountable to the worlds citizens. CIDA funds are not earmarked or conditional for (a) specific project(s) within NGLS's efforts, and it is NGLS that will determine how and where the resources provided by CIDA will be used. column19: TRIENNIAL COMPREHENSIVE POLICY REVIEW - CONTRIBUTION FY 2006/07
column20: Project Description: The 2008-10 TCPR (Triennial Comprehensive Policy Review) is scheduled for negotiation during the 62nd session of the General Assembly in the fall of 2007. To feed into this process, the UN Department of Economic and Social Affairs (UNDESA) is undertaking a comprehensive review of the TCPR to take stock of the effectiveness and results of the UN system's development cooperation during the 2005-07 period. The review will take into account the coordination structures and available capacity in the UN system to provide a comprehensive and appropriate response to developing countries' demands. It will also draw on the research papers prepared for the UN Panel on System-wide Coherence. UNDESA will undertake approximately ten research projects, varying from capacity building, national ownership, funding and the UN's evaluation function to human resources and relief to development transition. To do this, UNDESA is using existing evaluations and studies as its basis, complemented by consultations with a wide group of stakeholders both at country level and in New York. column20: Este Programa de saneamiento consiste en apartar a los menores, de manera temporal, del ambiente contaminado por radioactividad en el que habitualmente habitan. Numerosos estudios científicos han demostrado que la separación de los niños de la zona contaminada durante períodos de tiempo superioes a 40 días mejora notablemente el nivel de salud de los mismos, a la vez que se considera que aumenta la esperanza de vida de éstos entre 1 y 2 años por cada período de alejamiento temporal, según estimaciones.

Alumni outreach funds will be used by the Embassy’s Public Affairs Section to encourage networking among U.S. program alumni and their colleagues in fields that promote democratic advancement and economic reform. Through the administration of small grants to U.S. program alumni-linked organizations, the program will allow the Embassy to provide support to organizations or individuals for democracy-related activities such as community action projects, association building, promoting interethnic tolerance and understanding, and youth programs.
column28: Community participation and development

column20: The Embassy’s Democracy Commission gives small grants to local NGOs engaged in building the social and intellectual foundations of democracy, the democratic resolution of problems and the institutionalization of open, pluralistic political processes. All proposals are given a technical review in Washington, D.C., prior to a grant being issued by the Embassy.

The IIP Bureau’s U.S. Speakers Program strengthens public affairs outreach through the use of U.S. experts in a variety of policy-relevant fields for in-country training, lectures, workshops, seminars, and consultations. These experts pass along their practical skills, thereby creating a “multiplier” effect within the host country. U.S. Speakers Programs provide a wide range of perspectives, promote recognition of fundamental liberties and individual freedoms in the region, and increase civic participation.

column20: Assist special populations which may be vulnerable or at-risk on a temporary or chronic basis whose needs are not addressed under emergency humanitarian assistance or other programs. These include groups such as the disabled; orphans, children and at-risk youth; victims of trafficking; victims of gender-based violence; refugees, returnees, ethnic minorities, internally displaced or other socially excluded groups; the elderly; and female heads of household. Depending on circumstances, services may intend to protect groups; mitigate adverse conditions they face, or to remove barriers to help integrate them into society. Components may include measures to increase the capacity of local service and advocacy NGOs and/or professional social workers; to establish public/private service delivery partnerships as well as family and community focused service models; to establish effective referral networks; to develop appropriate service protocols and methods for screening prospective recipients; or to improve public understanding and sensitivity to the needs of the vulnerable. While services provided should not exclude victims of trafficking in persons, programs designed specifically for this group fall under the Peace and Security Objective under the Transnational Crime Area and the Trafficking in Persons and Migrant Smuggling Element. [through Pact]

column20: Improve the capacity of businesses to integrate into domestic and international markets through increases in productivity and improvements in corporate governance and the development and application of modern technology and marketing practices. Enhance the capacity of businesses and business associations in terms of their corporate governance capabilities and their application of best practices and technologies to achieve increased production and marketing of products and services. It includes adoption of efficient production processes, improved labor productivity, environmentally-sound management of natural resources and the development of accounting and management systems that can help the company and industry group implement business, labor, product and process standards that enhance business competitiveness. Business capacity development programs may include activities that help men- and women-owned firms and associations respond to these international markets and create regional alliances. [through United Nations Development Programme]

column20: Programa de acogida temporal de menores bielorrusos afectados por la catástrofe de Chernobyl :: A través del Convenio de colaboración con ANIDA se apoya el ?Programa de acogida temporal de menores bielorrusos afectados por la catástrofe de Chernobyl? Este programa ha facilitado la estancia sanitaria en Córdoba, desde el 21 de junio al 30 de agosto de 2012, de una delegación de 36 niños/as bielorrusos/as víctimas de la catástrofe nuclear de Chernobyl, destinada a la mejora de su salud. Durante esta estancia los/as menores han pasado un reconocimiento médico especializado para aquellos que padecen alguna patología, así como una asistencia odontológica a todos lo/as menores en los centros de salud correspondiente a las familias de acogida.También han disfrutado de actividades recreativas y culturas, destacando el acto municipal de acogida, celebrado el 11 de julio en La Ciudad de los Niños y la Jornada de Convivencia del 4 de agosto en el Pantano de Puente Nuevo y en el que participaron los/as menores con sus familias de acogida, disfrutando de un curso de iniciación de vela y paseos en barco por el pantano.

column20: I Acto de Acogida Infantil a menores saharauis y bielorrusos :: El 11 de julio de 2012 en la Ciudad de los/as Niños/as se celebró esta actividad cuyo objetivos eran conseguir un momento de juego y encuentro en el que menores saharauis (del programa Vacaciones en Paz de ACANSA) y bielorrusos (del Programa de Acogida Temporal a menores afectados por la catástrofe de Chernóbyl de ANIDA) se sientan acogidos por niños/as de nuestra ciudad y sus instituciones y dar a conocer a la infancia de Córdoba la situación que viven otros niños/as en el mundo.En este acto participaron las familias cordobesas de acogida y menores saharauis y bielorrusos, niños/as participantes de las Escuelas Municipales de Verano y otras familias interesadas. La participación se valora muy positivamente. En concreto fueron: 35 menores saharauis, 25 bielorrusos y 75 de las Escuelas de Verano , más otros niños/as cordobeses/as. Los menores fueron acompañados de sus familias.En su programa se contó con juegos infantiles, teatro-guiñol, música popular bielorrusa de acordeón, lecturas Infantiles y la siembra simbólica de un árbol por la paz y la amistad, a través de los cuales se trabajaron valores de interculturalidad y se conectaron las dos experiencias de acogida en nuestra ciudad.Este acto fue planificado y coordinado en todo momento con la Asociación Cordobesa Amigos de los Niños Saharuis (ACANSA) y con la Asociación ANIDA, así como con diferentes servicios municipales: la Delegación de Patrimonio, Casco Histórico y Naturaleza, la Delegación de Educación e Infancia, la Delegación de Infraestructuras, el INGEMA y la Ciudad de los Niños/as, coordinados a través de esta Delegación de Cooperación. --- original channelcode : 11003

column20: Project Description: Guidelines for Evaluation of GRPPs . IEG has completed a Sourcebook of Indicative Principles and Standards for Evaluating Global and Regional Partnership Programs (GRPPs) under the auspices of the OECD/DAC Network on Development Evaluation. A Stakeholder Consultative Workshop held in Paris to review the Sourcebook also called for the preparation of a second, companion document of good-practice guidelines and examples for the GRPPs members. The good-practice guidelines and examples will be aimed specifically at evaluators of GRPPs. The purpose is to improve the quality of program-level evaluations of GRPPs in order to enhance the relevance and effectiveness of the programs. The document will provide good practices for applying generally accepted evaluation criteria (such as relevance, effectiveness, efficiency, and sustainability) to the evaluation of GRPPs - along with positive examples from existing evaluations - in the light of the particular features of GRPPs. It will also provide good-practice guidelines and examples for assessing the more unique aspects of GRPPs such as their governance and management arrangements, their resource mobilization strategies, and their strategies for devolution or exit, as applicable. column18: Local Currency Risk Sharing Special Fund for Early Transition Countries (ETCs)
column19: LOCAL CURRENCY RISK SHARING SPECIAL FUND FOR EARLY TRANSITION COUNTRIES (ETCS)
column20: The overall goal of the EBRD Early Transition Countries (ETCs) Local Currency Initiative is to improve local capital markets and increase local currency lending. in close coordination with the IMF and other IFIs. The countries included are Armenia. Azerbaijan. Georgia. Belarus. Kyrgyzstan. Moldova. Tajikistan. Turkmenistan. Uzbekistan and Mongolia. In the framework of this wider Initiative. SECO has contributed 1.5 mio CHF to the Local Currency Risk Sharing Special Fund which aims to subsidise local currency lending. This is seen as a short term response. while interventions to address structural problems are being built up. ETC countries will have to commit themselves to macroeconomic reforms in order to benefit from EBRD loans. The Programme should yield benefits at the micro and macro level: At the macro level. the higher volume of local currency loans to the financial sector and to the corporate sector should reduce vulnerability to foreign exchange movements. resulting in lower insolvency risk and increased financial stability. At the micro level. the loans should help the local borrowers decrease their financial risk by matching liabilities to local currency revenues. SECO will closely monitor the wider roll out of the Initiative and may consider supporting specific interventions in the area of local capital markets development in its priority countries.
